\end_inset

.
 Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left(t_{0}\right)=1.5\times I_{p}$
\end_inset

 as the initial condition.
 Refactor the upper bounds 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Gamma}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\Gamma}$
\end_inset

 in the config and the code as multiples of the user-selected 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left(t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

, i.e., learning_rate_upper_bound_mult and learning_rate_lower_bound_mult
 or something like that.
 You can pick the system initial condition (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

).
 Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\widehat{\theta}}=0.001$
\end_inset

.
 Hard code 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(t_{0}\right)=\mathbf{0}_{n}$
\end_inset

 for both.
 Make sure it's still possible to add a custom additional signals to insight
 temporary excitation via 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Keep all config related this excitation signals.
 Run each sim for 30 seconds (sim time).
 To do this, we may need a new file (maybe .py or maybe just a sweep.sh).
 The research question is in what ways in the NN-in-the-integral controller
 better? Does it achieve better function approximation (not expected because
 neither update law is composite), require less RMS control effort, achieve
 better tracking (ceteris parabis gain, initial conditions, architecture
 size, and dynamics of course), and so on? Data to save, statistics to save,
 plots to save will otherwise be identical to existing code.
 
